{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501888"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:35:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:35:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1802"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1802"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.16,0.36,0.01,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1802"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97883"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49450"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to his primary care physician with a 12 month history of increasing pain in his left knee. The pain is exacerbated by walking or climbing stairs and is eased by rest. Paracetamol provides some pain relief. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes, hypertension and Stage 3 chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is a varus deformity of the left knee and mild tenderness over the lateral joint margin. The joint is stiff but there is a full range of movement. A plain X-ray of the knee shows loss of joint space, subchondral sclerosis and osteophyte formation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular diclofenac cream","Intra-articular hyaluronidase injection","Land based exercise","Curcumin","Intra-articular triamcinolone injection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and radiographic findings are characteristic of osteoarthritis. Over the counter pain relief such as paracetamol may provide some benefit to patients. Whilst some form of pain relief must be considered, prolonged courses of non-steroidal anti-inflammatories (NSAIDs) should be avoided however, especially in patients with renal impairment. Whilst there is less systemic absorption of cutaneous application compared with parentally administered NSAIDs, they must still be used with caution in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMainstays of treatment include weight loss if BMI is elevated, and physical therapy to improve joint stability through muscle strengthening via \u003Cstrong\u003Eland based exercises\u003C/strong\u003E. These might include walking, weightlifting and yoga, as opposed to swimming. Intra-articular injections have also been shown to confer benefit in OA patients, however in a randomised controlled trial of both treatment modalities, patients who underwent physical therapy had less pain and functional disability at 12 months without the adverse effects associated with pharmacological interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurcumin (active compound in tumeric) is advocated as an anti-inflammatory herbal preparation, but is of unproven value.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Muscle strengthening via land based exercises should be the first step in the management of osteoarthritis."],"references":["Deyle G, Allen C, Allison S, Gill N, Hando B, Petersen E et al. Physical Therapy versus Glucocorticoid Injection for Osteoarthritis of the Knee. New England Journal of Medicine. 2020;382(15):1420-1429.","RACGP Pathway for Diagnosis \u0026 Management of Knee and Hip Osteoarthritis [Internet]. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/fb2a6ac2-892a-4ba4-98c2-c984ea25e4a9/Algorithm-Holistic-assessment-diagnosis-and-management-of-knee-and-hip-osteoarthritis.pdf.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97883"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1802"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97883"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-25T21:05:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T21:06:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1802"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end 